The type specimen reportedly deposited at the Museu Nacional de História Natural, Lisbon, Portugal , was not examined in this study. However, several specimens presently deposited at MNHN , RMNH and USNM were examined, which agree with descriptions and illustrations of previous workers (
Brito Capello 1866
;
Capart 1951
;
Monod 1956
;
Guinot 1979
).

Ecology and geographical distribution.
Glyptoxanthus angolensis
has been found in shallow to moderate subtidal depths (to 40 m ), in sandy-rocky, rocky or coralline substrate. It is known to occur on the western coast of Africa: Ghana , Senegal , Angola , São Tomé , Annobon , Sierra Leone , and Gabon (see
Manning & Holthuis 1981
). The live colouration of this species has been described as generally red, with lighter patches of yellow (
Brito Capello 1866
) or orange-red with lighter patches (
Capart 1951
).
